First, build a new docker image with an image name of "puppet-node". This
will be used to create the nodes that are being controlled by the puppet
server. They are Ubuntu images, with base tools installed, as well as
the puppet-agent package. A continous loop will also run on the image
which will run the puppet agent command every 30 seconds.

docker build -t puppet-node .


Now that the image is created, start the docker compose. This will start
three containers: one is the puppet server using a public image, the other
two are the puppet nodes using the image created above.

docker-compose up -d

NOTE: You can view the logs either through Docker Desktop if you have that
instaled, or via command:

docker container logs puppet-node1-1

(Where "puppet-node1-1" is the container name). When the container first starts,
you will likely see errors at first. This is because the puppet server isn't fully
up and running yet. But when the script checks again in 30 seconds, it should
work eventually.


In one terminal, connect to one of the puppet nodes:

docker exec -it puppet-node2-1 bash

Run "ps aux" and verify that "nginx" is not running. Next, in another terminal, 
connect to the puppet server, using the following:

docker exec -it puppet-puppet-1 bash

Once you are connected to the server, create a new file in the following location:
/etc/puppetlabs/code/environments/production/manifests
Filename: site.pp

NOTE: You likely will need to install a tool such as nano:
apt update
apt install nano

Contents of file:

node default {
  package { 'nginx':
    ensure => installed,
  }

  package { 'squid':
    ensure => absent,
  }

  service { 'nginx':
    ensure => running,
    enable => true,
  }
}


Once the file is saved, it will get applied the next time the puppet nodes run
the puppet agent process (every 30 seconds). Switch back to the terminal that
is connected to one of the nodes, and check if nginx process is showing.

Validate with curl as well:
apt install curl
curl http://localhost

Next, install "squid" and verify installed:
apt install squid
whereis squid

Wait 30 seconds, and check if squid was removed. (Note the configurations will
still be there)


